Thanks for pointing to openHFT. Yes, I went through multiple Java implementations including this one. The reason I decided to use smhasher as the source of truth was, the smhasher implementation includes comprehensive tests to cover the attributes for measuring goodness of a non-cryptographic hash function. And these attributes are subtle and could be found out to be a problem maybe only on certain lengths of input. So when I looked at these implementations, I checked what tests they have done first. And since there is no such tests(test multiple attributes and lengths) in these Java implementations to prove the hash functions are correct or good. So I decided to start from smhasher implementations and used the results generated from smhasher to verify any other(including drill's) implementation.

